Fit Scoring Framework
Before tailoring a resume or writing a cover letter, score the role. This drives a structured decision about where to invest time and if you can position yourself credibly for the role.

This framework has two parts: a score and a gap map.


The Score
Rate overall fit as a percentage. The number isn't precise — it's a forcing function for clear-eyed assessment.

Thresholds:

80%+ — cold application worth pursuing. Strong enough to invest in full tailoring.
70%+ with a warm referral — worth pursuing. A referral closes some of the gap; the conversation can do the rest.
Below 70% — proceed carefully. Either find a referral, or be honest about whether the investment is worth it.

These aren't hard rules. A 68% fit at a company you deeply want to work for, with a referral in place, is a different conversation than a 68% fit on a cold application to a company you're lukewarm about.


Scoring Credibly
The score means nothing if it's inflated. Two things cause inflated scores:

1. Scoring from the job title rather than the JD. A title match feels like fit. It isn't. Read the actual requirements and score against those. Note explicitly when you're inferring fit from context rather than from JD language — those inferences are weaker and should be weighted accordingly.

2. Counting adjacent experience as direct experience. If you've worked near something but haven't owned it, say so. "CPQ-adjacent" is not "CPQ ownership." The gap will surface in interviews if you don't surface it yourself first.


The Gap Map
For each of the role's core requirements — aim for 5-8, decoded from the JD into plain English — mark one of four categories:

Category
What it means
Already strong
On your resume, evidenced, defensible in an interview
Present but buried
In your history but not visible on the current resume — surface it
In your experience, missing from resume
Real experience that hasn't been written up yet — mine your Memory Bank
Genuine gap
You don't have this, or your exposure is too thin to claim it


Be precise about specific gaps. Vague gaps are hard to address. A specific gap ("I haven't owned xxx platform end-to-end, but I did own the adjacent workflows, and here are the parallels between tools I did own and ones in the desired stack") can be reframed confidently. A gap you've papered over will surface at the worst moment.


Addressing Genuine Gaps
For each genuine gap, prepare three things:

Honest framing — what you do have that's adjacent or analogous.

The reframe — how to position it without overclaiming. Lead with what's real, then bridge to the gap.

The line — a specific, natural-sounding response you can actually say in an interview. Write it out. Vague intentions don't survive the moment.

Example:

Gap: No direct xxx console administration experience
Honest framing: Governed SSO and access controls across a 25+ app portfolio, worked closely with the team that managed xxx
Reframe: "I haven't been hands-on in the xxx console myself — that sat with our identity team. What I have is the governance and integration layer: access policy design, provisioning workflows, the security review process. The console is learnable; the judgment around it takes longer."


A Note on Fit Scores Over Time
Track your scores across applications. Patterns emerge.

If you're consistently scoring 85%+ and not getting interviews, the scores are probably inflated. If you're getting interviews at 72% and offers at 68%, your referral network is doing more work than the scores suggest. You may be surprised at what carries more weight than you realize. One recruiter told me my resume stood out because of my international background. That wasn’t stated as a JD requirement and I may have passed over the submission had I worked off scores alone.


Quick Scoring Checklist
Before submitting any application:

Decoded the JD into 5-8 plain-English requirements
Scored each requirement honestly (not from the title)
Flagged any scores inferred from context rather than JD text
Mapped all requirements to one of the four gap categories
Prepared a reframe for each genuine gap
Applied the 80/70 threshold to decide whether to proceed
Noted whether a referral is in play and how that changes the calculus


Note: I periodically re-score a sheet of opportunities using a different model, and feed back past results for a refreshed score view.
